                  <tr><td>25</td><td>3.125</td><td>2.980</td></tr>
                  <tr><td>50</td><td>6.25</td><td>5.960</td></tr>
                  <tr><td>100</td><td>12.5</td><td>11.921</td></tr>
                  <tr><td>300</td><td>37.5</td><td>35.763</td></tr>
                  <tr><td>1000 (1 Gbps)</td><td>125</td><td>119.209</td></tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>

              <p class="muted" style="margin: 10px 0 0;">
                Tip: If your download shows <strong>~12 MB/s</strong>, your connection is roughly <strong>~100 Mbps</strong> (before overhead).
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Panel: Examples -->
          <div data-panel="examples">
            <div class="option-block">
              <div class="option-title">
                <h2>Real-World Examples</h2>
                <div class="hint">How it feels in daily use</div>
              </div>

              <ul style="margin: 8px 0 0; padding-left: 18px;">
                <li><strong>100 Mbps</strong> internet ≈ <strong>12.5 MB/s</strong> max download on a perfect connection.</li>
                <li>A <strong>5 GB</strong> game update at <strong>100 Mbps</strong> takes about <strong>~6–7 minutes</strong> (best case).</li>
                <li>If Steam shows <strong>50 MB/s</strong>, that corresponds to about <strong>400 Mbps</strong> (50 × 8).</li>
              </ul>

              <div style="height: 10px;"></div>

              <div class="option-title">
                <h2>Common Mistakes</h2>
                <div class="hint">Avoid confusion</div>
              </div>

